WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And Mr. Gia, thanks for doing this interview.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:15.000
It's a pleasure.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Now you were born and grew up in Paschristian, Mississippi, and you said that racial prejudice by and large did not affect you during your youth.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
How could that be so in Mississippi at that age and time?

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I come from the most non-mississippi-like section of Mississippi.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.000
There was a heavy Catholic influence.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Angleship Yard was produced in most of the major armaments for all hostilities in Paschristian,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
and hiring people from 63 counties.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:51.000
So you had the Labor Union influence, you had the Catholic Church influence, which was tremendous.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And you had a population of 100,000 white people, 19,000 black people.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:08.000
The Catholic Church in 1957 or 58 made a decision that we were going to desegregate the schools.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And they did it this way.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
The announcement was we have two programs.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
We have excommunication, and we have integration.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Make your choice by Friday.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Now there was violence going on in Louisiana.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:24.000
Nothing happened on the Gulf Coast.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:32.000
So I learned, first hand, that institutions can really have an impact on social policy.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:39.000
I was fortunate enough to, I bought three slot machines, Julia, because there was a lot of gambling on the Gulf Coast.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:45.000
And I was, I just passed the academic test for interest in Tuvalu College.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
And I was going to be sent to jail by Gaston Hughes.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.000
My father hires Biddle Adams to represent me.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Who is Biddle Adams is the Lieutenant Governor Under Billbow.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
He's the chairman of the Democratic Party in the state of Mississippi.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
And he's a lawyer who represents black people who have been accused of raping white women.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
We go to his office, and my father says his problem.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:13.000
And Biddle said, don't worry about it.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.000
He calls up Gaston Hughes.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
He said, no, this boy is not black.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.000
He's a Creole.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.000
I didn't correct him, Julia.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And he then says, well, you know, this boy is going off to school.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
I don't want to hear anymore about these slot machines.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And Gaston said, well, I'm a send-in department.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And Biddle said, okay.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:32.000
And I looked at my father.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.000
We must be in the wrong place.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:35.000
But he continues to say, okay.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:42.000
He said, but if I hear anymore about these slot machines, I'm going to call for federal investigation of all gambling on the Gulf Coast.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And I'm going to make sure that everyone knows that you caused it.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
At the time of this meeting, I was 17 years old.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
I'm now 71 years of age.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
I have never heard about those slot machines.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And I've never heard about anyone who's heard about those slot machines.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:04.000
We should drove home to me that all of the life that we live is political.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
So you're going to make a back up a little bit.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
You're sitting in the office of Theodore Bilbo.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:09.000
No, no.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:10.000
A Biddle Adam.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So what Adam?

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Who was Lieutenant Governor?

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Yeah, right.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.000
While when Bilbo was governor.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:15.000
All right.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
I was born in Harrison County.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Bilbo was born in Hancock County.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:27.000
Biddle Adams, after leaving Lieutenant Governor's ship, then becomes a practice in lawyer.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
And a loyal Kennedy Democrat.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
This was the guy who handled the Patriots for the Democratic Party.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
I come out of a family.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:44.000
My grandfather's brother was chairman of the Republican Party in Hancock County for 65 years.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.000
He died at 105 years of age.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
His name is Lewis Piennaz, P-I-R-N-S.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:57.000
So he and I talked about Randolph, who my high school was named after.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.000
We talked about, he said, I saw the Civil War fought on the beaches of Bay St. Louis.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Not far from Waverland where we've used to go down to meet.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
And he talked about my wife and I did a genealogy study.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:13.000
And we run across a WPA interview of him.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And he says, well, you know, Bilbo is really terrible.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
And I just hope that blacks will be able to fight they were into the Democratic Party.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And I got chills on my mind.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
That's what I've been doing.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So my family was very, very political.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.000
My grandfather was a man who taught me the value of listening.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
He would have, long before I communiqued him was what it is today.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
He had a lot of Baptist ministers as brands.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And they would meet outside every Sunday and they would decide what they were going to go ahead and convince him of.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
And I knew who was going to this argument.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:58.000
So my, he would go here and they would come out convinced that they'd convinced my grandfather.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
And they were satisfied that he understood them and he agreed with them.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And I knew, when I talked to him about after that, it had gone just the other way.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
But he had one habit, Julian.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
He said, if you went to him and said, Mr. Jews, I'm going fishing.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:19.000
He would repeat the word fishing and I said, Grandpa, you too smart to do that.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
I've seen the people you talk to.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And he said, boy, it gives me a little bit more time to think about what I'm going to say.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
From that day on, Julian, I never questioned my grandfather.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
He and I read the newspaper together every day.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And we also listened to two people on radio.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
Whenever they were FDR spoke, he gathered the family that listened to our president.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And another guy was Ronald Reagan.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Really? Why Reagan?

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Why Reagan? Because we liked his style.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
We didn't like his ideology.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
But we were impressed with how he did it.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I mean, he could paint the pictures.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And so he takes me, I'm seven years old, he takes me in front of the Catholic Church in Mississippi.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:08.000
And in St. Philomines, and I read Paul's letters to the Galatians and Ephesians.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
And I'm just proud.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
I'm with my grandfather.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.000
I can read before my congregation.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:16.000
I can do anything.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:17.000
Right.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:28.000
So I learned from my family the value of service and the interrelationship between religion and politics.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:34.000
My father was a man who would have made Lyndon Johnson look like a piker.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.000
You know, really?

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
If he could have just gotten the kind of political opportunities that I had.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.000
My father got in a contest one time with about a mathematics problem.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.000
And then the town told him that he was wrong, but he had figured it out wrong.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And they sent to the book manufacturers, and the book manufacturers said, we made a mistake.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.000
He's right.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:03.000
He's a man who, when he goes into a jury, a woman wanted to get $6,000 from an insurance company.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:06.000
And everybody in the jury said, oh, that's, that's you.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And my father said, well, send out and get a lot of coffee.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.000
Because until she gets $6,000, $6,000, we're not going to decide anything.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:23.000
I saw my father, Julian, beat one of the richest men in Paschristin, almost to a pulp in front of the post office with his fist,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
and then take me by the hand and walk me home.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:34.000
See, I come from a city that was the Catholic Church at desegregated.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
I could use any restaurant I want.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
I could go into any drugstore I want.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
I could ride on the bus in a time.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
Anyway, I was a long showman at 13.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
I used the white restaurant on the golf coast.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Only Dr. Felix Dunn, who was a black wealthy political person, and myself did that.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.000
Now, I did it not because I had anything to do with nonviolence.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:02.000
I did it because my father would have killed any 20 people that had anything to say to me.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:08.000
But then you know that there was a great difference between where you lived in Mississippi and the rest of Mississippi.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And how did you balance in your mind the fact that you were able to do these things here?

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
But just a few miles away, you would take your life in your hands to do them.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
What really brought this home to me was I went to Tukeloo College.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:27.000
Tukeloo College was threatened with extinction by the state legislature.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.000
It had an interracial faculty.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:31.000
It was perfectly designed for me.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
I needed to be someplace that was academically free.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:42.000
That would be committed to social change, and that would be committed to empowerment and the development of leadership.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
Tukeloo was all about that.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
And when I get there, I meet Ed King.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
I meet David Broder.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:51.000
I meet Ernest Berinsky.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:56.000
Ernest Berinsky is a Jew driven out of Germany.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
He comes to Tukeloo. He becomes an institution there.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:06.000
And he develops a theory that some institutions are functional only by their absence of function.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
That's the Democratic Party of Mississippi.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
You don't need to be organized every four years.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
They go to a convention. They come back and they disband.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
Because if they don't disband, then they have to answer people's problems.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
But you can run the state apparatus without doing that.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
I meet A.A. Branch.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.000
A.A. Branch is a member of the leadership of the YMCA.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.000
A.A. Branch says to us,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:38.000
the policy of Tukeloo is you can become involved in any demonstration you want around voting.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
We're going to assist you in doing that.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:41.000
But take your books with you.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
We're going to test you just like everyone else.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Only Tukeloo College and Miles College did that.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:51.000
No other college in the South or in America did that to my knowledge.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
So I'm in the perfect place for me.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
I meet people who are committed to nonviolence.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
I meet people.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:06.000
I meet Salta, John Salta, who teaches me everything I need to know about socialism.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:15.000
I meet people who are committed to A.A. Branch is a leader of the YWCA.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
But it's A.A. Branch who walks into the Cofford office in 1964 with the papers.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
To join with the United Church of Christ and the National Council of Churches

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:29.000
in taking over the WLBT television station.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
Tell me the name before you jump this far here.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Tell me the names of some of the students you went to school with,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
whom we know as movement people.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.000
I went to school with Dory Ladden.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:39.000
Enjoy.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.000
Joy Sladden.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:48.000
Quite a few people from Franklin.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Johnny Frazier, who was one of the leaders.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:58.000
He wasn't a student there, but I worked in conjunction with him.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Quite a few people.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:01.000
No.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:08.000
The Anderson, who later becomes a member of the State Supreme Court.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:15.000
I know this is counterfactual, but what if he had gone to Jackson State instead of Tugeloo?

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:19.000
How would you, how would large-guide have turned out?

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
I don't think I would have lasted it too.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
I mean at Jackson State.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:35.000
Because I believe I'd come up in a town that created certain political expectations of how

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
what was expected of me by my family and by my church.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:50.000
So I wouldn't have fit into the conformity, the strict rigid conformity and hierarchical leadership of Jackson State.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
Dory Ladden and Joyce Ladden went there first and they had to leave there and come to Tugeloo.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
Tugeloo was an Oasis in the state of Mississippi.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
It was committed to academic freedom, committed to growth, to leadership.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:07.000
And it was, it's very existence was threatened by the state legislature, but they continued to move ahead.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:14.000
Again, let me back up a little bit. I was just thinking about past Christian and the neighborhood, the community grew up in.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.000
The Catholic Church's influence, the influence of labor unions.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
Most of Mississippi doesn't have this. Most of the South doesn't have this.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.000
It's right.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:27.000
It's only when you get into Louisiana that there's any real Catholic presence.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
And outside of your section of Mississippi, probably not much, any place else.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.000
And the same would be true of Alabama, Georgia and so on.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:43.000
You ever consider how lucky you were to run into the Catholic Church and deliver a community where labor unions flourished?

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
Let me add one other thing to it and I'll respond to your question.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
You also had Kisla Air Force Base, which was a major dynamo.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:56.000
But yes, I consider myself very fortunate. I was born in the right town.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:02.000
I get to go to the right church. I get to go to the right college and then I run into SNCC.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:15.000
And I come from a family that understands that in 1964, my uncle, my favorite uncle, says to me,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:19.000
the mayor wants to meet with you about the summer project.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:25.000
And I go up to his, walk up the steps to his house, he says, but I don't want you to call him from my house.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
My uncle scared about being tired of this.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
But I go down and talk to the mayor and we talk, I said, here's what we're going to do.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
And they say, here's what we're going to do.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:38.000
And I say, I give no quarter, they give no quarter.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And then this is 64. In 66, that same uncle runs for Alderman in Paschristin.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:54.000
So you get an idea of the impact of the 1965 Vodernich Act.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
A moment ago, you said you ran into SNCC. Tell me about running into SNCC.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:00.000
How did that happen?

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
Who embodied SNCC for you?

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Dory Ladna, Joyce Ladna and Bob Moses.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
I meet Bob Moses, John Doer and Marion Barry all at the same time.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:21.000
They've come out of McCone. We're all working at 714 Roll Street.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:32.000
There we have Moses, the Ladna's, Bevel, Diane, quite a few other folks.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:37.000
But Levin Brown, Sheila Michaels, this is the Freedom House, right?

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
From there, we move into the Delta.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:46.000
We go to Ames and Moore's house. Ames and Moore Park pass us along to Joe McDonnell and Mississons.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:50.000
And we run across a lady named Fannie Lou Hamel.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:57.000
Bevel, myself, McLauren, and Farman go to a mass meeting.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:02.000
We open the call for anyone who wants to go down and register. Fannie Lou Hamel raises her hand.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:09.000
And we run across a woman who is a religious fundamentalist who knows the Bible.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:15.000
A woman who has a perfect sense of timing in a speech pattern.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:23.000
She can weigh yeap together three different issues and collapse them in 25-were age and bring it all together.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:28.000
She's a woman who walks into churches and who takes over.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:32.000
If the minister is a good minister, she treats him as a good minister.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:37.000
If he's wavering, she preaches to him before his congregation.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
And nobody says a word to her.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:54.000
So here we get the perfect melding of religious fundamentalism and pragmatic politics.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:59.000
Because not only does she go to register, but as you know, she becomes a national celebrity.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:05.000
She becomes a woman who Andy Young takes to meet with Senator Church when he wants to talk about Vietnam.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
She's one of the founders of the National Women's Political Caucus.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:16.000
She's the woman who speaks at the 64 Democratic Convention and Lyndon Johnson calls a press conference to interrupt her.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:24.000
But at that time, there was only ABC and CBS and they all play her speech in its entirety that evening.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:30.000
And then there are 1200 telegrams saying to seek the Freedom Democratic Party.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:36.000
And then Lyndon has to apply pressure because Lyndon says, and he says it in his tapes.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
The good thing about Lyndon is we got tapes on him.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:44.000
Lyndon says, look, we can't have a floor fight on this.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:52.000
We can't have a floor fight to seek an all-white delegation and then go and ask black people to vote for us in November.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.000
So the floor fight must be stopped.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:59.000
And then as president of the United States, he pulled out all of the stops.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:06.000
Delegates from California were told, one of them was told, your husband can be a federal judge.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
All you got to do is stop voting for the Freedom Democratic Party.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Candidates in New York were told, you all have a lot of OEO money as you know the office back in town.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:20.000
And you can keep it as long as you stop supporting the freedom.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:28.000
They went to the delegates in California and unfortunately the Democratic Party had passed the delegation supporting their position.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
But the president put all of his pressure on all of them.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:37.000
So, and as you know, we couldn't get the floor fight and not being able to get the floor fight.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:41.000
We would then offer a compromise of two people, which to the...

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:46.000
I'm proud of the fact that I'm the chairman of the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
I mean, jailed and had his verdict Mississippi.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:52.000
And I couldn't have given a speech as good as Senator Hamed did.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:18:02.000
And I couldn't have led the Freedom Democratic Party into making what I consider the most courageous, pragmatic political decision in American politics.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
They said to this compromise, no.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:17.000
Now, and it's interesting, some historians, as you know, by Rustin comes out late after that with an article called The Difference between Politics and Protest in Commentary Magazine.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:29.000
But what I am so proud of is no delegation went to the 64 Democratic Convention who understood the relationship between dying and the right to vote.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Every one of these people who had lost money, had served time in jail, had had their names posted in the newspaper when they registered to vote.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:46.000
But they were willing to take on the strongest political organization in the state of Mississippi, the Democratic Party.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And they were willing to go into Lyndon Johnson's Convention and fighting it as though it was their Convention.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
Let me back you up one more time.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Okay.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
You're going to Tugulu and your majoring in biology and minoring in philosophy.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Why'd you choose these fields? What was your career plan then?

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.000
My career plan then was become a doctor.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:12.000
And then I ran into chemistry and I changed my career plan.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:15.000
I just couldn't...

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:23.000
Now, when I tested while in Tugulu, I scored off the charts on everything except mathematics and chemistry.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:28.000
Well, there was no way I was going to be a doctor having no side. I made it a shift.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:32.000
What would you have been?

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:35.000
If I had had my brothers, I'd have been a lawyer.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
And why did you go that way?

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:49.000
Why did I go that way? Because I understood the universality of both of politics and how much the judiciary had framed that.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:20:01.000
I understood that the Brown case, I understood that the Baker versus Carl now opened up the political arena to the courts, which meant that there would be more power.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
And history proves me right on that.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:16.000
And we have reached a point in this country where we have an excellent power and scope of the judiciary and now we've got to fight to keep it.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:21.000
Now, you mentioned a moment ago about running into Bob Moses and the Latiners, sisters, and so on.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:26.000
And finding this community of people who make up the student on the Bollock-Courtney Committee.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.000
What did you think of them?

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
What did you think of them?

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:37.000
And how, in your mind, did they differ from the run of the middle college students and others you were associated with?

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:55.000
I thought that these were people who had a religious commitment to interracialism, that they were fundamentally about change, that they had, they were different from the other organizers I'd been exposed to, and that they were not about creating membership.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:00.000
They were about creating empowerment. And that is what fascinated me.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:15.000
Because here were people who were very well educated, who could think on their feet, who were interdependent, and who had fierce respect for one another.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:24.000
And then I got, once I saw how they operated, then I was totally captivated.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:34.000
Their position was that they were going to work with established leaders who were there, EW Steptoe, later Hartman Turnbull.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:39.000
They go into McComb, I don't go into McComb.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:48.000
Snickers almost killed, almost shot out of McComb. But what it discovers is that the black community will protect and support them.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:55.000
It will hide them, it will feed them, it will clothe them, it will arrive for them, it will do anything to protect them.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:05.000
And this carries us into the Delta. And there we go into Greenwood. And we find that in Greenwood, Mississippi, there was tremendous fear.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:11.000
But most of us propose, let's have some, and I said, no, they don't know us yet.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:17.000
So we got a known, moving around, and then we had demonstrations.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:22.000
We had 100 people come into the jail to bring us food and support.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:28.000
That's not supposed to happen. I mean, what is the one thing black people learn? Don't go to jail.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:33.000
Don't be associated with those who go to jail. If you're their friends, where can tell they get out of jail?

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:44.000
So what we, and we push Greenwood to the point where we have 500 people come down to register to vote.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:54.000
Hardly lot. A segregationist lawyer who defends Byron D. LeBeckworth says to me in the, the Flore County Courthouse one,

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:59.000
you should be very proud of how many people you all got coming down in the Flore County.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:05.000
I said, well, Mr. Lot, I understand we got them coming down and y'all are turning them away from registration.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:10.000
What we need to do is create a situation where they can come down and get registered.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:14.000
He said, well, that's going to be a good fight and it improved to be a good fight.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:19.000
Because what we were able to do in Greenwood is force the Department of Justice.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Once we, the voter registration workers got arrested there.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:28.000
John Doors says, okay, we're going into court.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:34.000
But instead of filing a type A suit, his files are types B suit was just, gets us out.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:44.000
But what we found was that the, the Department of Justice to this day defends their position by saying,

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:48.000
we didn't want to occupy the Flore County.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:53.000
Because remember, as, while this was going on, there was also the case of, of, of,

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:57.000
Ole Miss and there was the case of Theron Lynn.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:07.000
And so we were able to, I think one of the major achievements of SNCC was to bring about a work in relationship with the Department of Justice.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:13.000
We trained them. We took John Door to Warthall County.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:17.000
And we introduced John Door to a man named John Hardy.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:22.000
John Hardy was a SNCC activist who went, brought some people into the register to vote.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:29.000
Mr. Woods, the registrar, hit him with a gun and a stick and the Department of Justice said, wait a minute.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.000
We're going to stop this prosecution.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:35.000
We're going to, and the reason we're stopping is when you hit him,

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:41.000
when you hit him, you hit every black man who want, a woman who might want to come to register to vote.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:46.000
So they develop a theory called, on appeal, an injunction pending appeal.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
And that's what they do.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
You can't prosecute this man.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:54.000
And they take it to the fifth-selicant court of appeals. That's right.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:58.000
But could we say that one of the reasons that happened is because of somebody like John Door,

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:04.000
not because the Department itself, because somebody like John Door stood out among his fellows

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
and pushed hard for these kind of remedies.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:13.000
There's an absolute, John Door was not the ordinary Department of Justice.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:19.000
John Door believed in going into the field, finding out where the danger was,

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:23.000
and regardless, he, and he trained his staff to do that.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.000
And, well, good, so there's no question.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:33.000
John Door participates not only in that, but John Door also, when the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party,

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:41.000
files the first private lawsuit under the Voting Rights Act of 1965,

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:44.000
John Door and the Department of Justice, files in Amicus.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:47.000
We go to the Supreme Court, we win it, eight to one.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:53.000
And what does that case say? That case says, right now, the law says that the Attorney General

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
is the only one who can institute suits.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:02.000
We're going to take the position that, from this day forward, anyone who is aggrieved by Section 5

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:05.000
has the right to bring a lawsuit under Section 5.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:09.000
Do you see the range that they're given?

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.000
They broaden Section 5.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:14.000
They give us the best possible interpretation again.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.000
Now, this case is my idea.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:21.000
I read a book called Get In His Trumpet by Anthony Lewis,

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:25.000
and it describes Lyndon Johnson as someone who stole his election.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:31.000
And I knew I'd been trained well enough to know that if you had the choice,

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:38.000
between trained by being given guidance by a thief or by a bishop,

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:41.000
choose the thief.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.000
The bishop will tell you, no, this is not right.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:48.000
The thief will tell you, this is how I did it.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:51.000
And this is how I've stopped other people from doing it.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:56.000
I knew that Lyndon Johnson didn't want anyone to ever be able to do what he had done.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:03.000
And I go in a Section 5, and it said, it's the most beautiful language ever written.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:16.000
It says that any change by a covered political subdivision that has the possibility of

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:21.000
deluging the voting rights act must either be pre-cliared by the Department of Justice

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:26.000
or litigated before a three-judge pound only in the District Columbia.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
Most beautiful words have ever heard.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:31.000
So what we do, once we win that case before the Supreme Court,

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:38.000
everyone, all lawyers in the South, switch from the 15th Amendment to Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:42.000
Now, the work you're doing with the student-owned violent court in the EGM,

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:46.000
these colleagues that you mentioned earlier, doesn't come without a cost.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.000
And you're beaten a couple of times.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.000
I don't know if it's painful for you to now to talk about that.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.000
Tell us about these two things.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.000
At these two cases where you were beaten.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:04.000
One of them was in Winona, Van Allue, Hamer, and Ann Elpanda, James West,

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:08.000
June Johnson, or returning from a South Carolina meeting.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:13.000
They stopped in Winona, they are arrested.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:16.000
I call and I said, did you have these people?

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.000
You said, well, come on over and find out.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.000
And I go over and I know they're there.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:23.000
And they beat me almost to death.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:30.000
And they want me to sign a statement saying, I drove over there and fell out of a car and hurt myself.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:33.000
I said, I'm not going to sign there.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:37.000
I'd never driven a car in my life and I started working outside the church.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:44.000
This caused our money to get some water for you one second.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:52.000
I leave Greenwood and I go into Winona.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:56.000
And I'm beaten.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:02.000
They threaten to burn my testicles with wooden sticks.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:07.000
I know that I have to stay conscious otherwise they're going to kill me.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:13.000
I'm beaten by 12 people and I'm asked to sign a statement which I refuse to sign.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.000
Then they charged me with murder.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
Who had you killed?

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:21.000
I hadn't killed anyone.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:23.000
I mean, who did they say you killed?

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:29.000
I had a note from someone who had said to me, who had given in the street, someone had been killed.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:33.000
And they took that and said, well, you killed them.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:41.000
And what I found was that I knew that I wasn't going to get out of the porch out of Winona alive.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:44.000
And I didn't think any of us that were there.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:47.000
The only thing, they left my cell to open.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:49.000
They left a knife outside.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
They sent someone who showed me a fake badge saying, I'm an FBI agent.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.000
I tell them it would really happen.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:30:00.000
And Medgea Evers was killed while we were in Winona.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:04.000
Which then, because they turned off the radio, I knew something that had tragic had happened.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
I just didn't know who.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:13.000
And then Andy Young, Bevel, and Frank Smith come to get me out of jail.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:20.000
And then we eventually go to the Medgea, I was funeral, and then I leave then go to Howdy Spurry.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:26.000
But it was clear to me that we were beaten too badly.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:31.000
I mean, we were beaten almost beyond recognition.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:37.000
And they were not going to allow us to go back and have pictures taken.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:42.000
Unfortunately, as far as it is, I believe that there are two things that saved our lives.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:49.000
One, Roberta Gala, and other people from across the country start calling in to ask to speak to us.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:52.000
The other, let them know that other people know they're in.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:56.000
And number two, the assassination of Medgea Evers.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
I just don't think.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:03.000
The other time that I had been beaten quite a few other times.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:09.000
But one time that I remember vividly, that I wasn't beaten, but I think it's something I want to talk about now.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:14.000
We were driving in a car from Howdy Spurry, Staxon.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:19.000
And it was a car that couldn't go over 50 miles an hour, had bad tires.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:24.000
And some people with shotguns were behind us, and I said, stop the car.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:30.000
And I got out, I walked back, and I looked at the piece, and I said, look, the FBI has a father in us.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:35.000
If you want to go to jail for 10 years, just do anything to anybody in that car.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:39.000
And then good old boys turned around, and then we got back in the car.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.000
Yes, you get a lie.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:50.000
But I'd rather lie and take control of my life, then to leave it to someone else who I didn't think had my good being intentions.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:32:00.000
Now, a lot of homes, Norton, who's the district's representative to the Congress, has known you since the early 1960s.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.000
Back, did she come with you to get the people out of jail in Manona?

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:04.000
She was involved.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:05.000
She was a young lawyer then.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:06.000
She was a lawyer?

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:07.000
Yes, she was involved.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:09.000
She said, you walked right into terror.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:10.000
What did she mean by that?

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:16.000
She said that at a dinner that was given in my name here in Washington.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:25.000
And what she, the way she laid it out was, and then she said, look, all black southern men were taught, stay out of jail.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:30.000
If your friends were in jail, send them money, pray for them, but don't go visit them.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:38.000
And he was a man who knew that there were civil rights workers arrested, and he went right into jail knowing what the terror was.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:41.000
And he looked at terror and walked right into it.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
I felt very complimented about that.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:58.000
Now, can you tell us quickly what differences were between the NAACP, long established organization, active across the state of Mississippi, SCLC, relatively new organization.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:08.000
How do these organizations differ in the ways they operated in Mississippi with SNCC, NAACP, SCLC, SNCC?

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:21.000
The NAACP took the position and I'm quoting Roy Wilkins, who said this part of this on the great documentary, Eyes on the Prize.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.000
Mississippi is a beast of state.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:30.000
It should be cut off and allowed to be trusted to see anyone who, he didn't say this on camera, he said it later.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
Anyone who attempts to organize is crazy.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:37.000
We're going to raise money out of the atrocities of Mississippi and move forward.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:41.000
We're going to litigate there when possible, and that's it.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:34:04.000
SCLC is a tough problem to answer because everything that was done that shows how creative, how pluralistic, how indigenous, and how really sophisticated the politics of SNCC in Mississippi was, was backed by Martin Luther King.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:08.000
So we got to separate Martin Luther King from SCLC.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:13.000
Martin Luther King supported us in the Freedom Election, in which we got 80,000 borders.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:25.000
He supported us in the summer project, which we were able to really create the Freedom Democratic Party, create the Freedom Schools, create the Wednesday group by Dorothy Height, the Wednesday group,

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.000
was bringing in black and white women from across the country.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:37.000
They meet with people who are in the movement and then go back and talk to their ministers, their bishops, their newspapers, and their senators and their congressmen.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:44.000
We also create the Freedom Schools, which are to this day carried out by the Children's Defense Fund.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:51.000
Now, why is there this difference, this economy between Martin Luther King, the head of SCLC and SCLC?

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:56.000
Why is he behaving in one way, and the organization he has behaving in another way?

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:58.000
Well, I'll tell you why.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:06.000
I think what he appreciated was the freedom and the creativity of what was going on in Mississippi.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:17.000
Here, here we were persuading, sending a message to the country that if you allow us to vote in Mississippi, unimpeded, we will do it.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:20.000
80,000 people back that up.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:24.000
We said about the 64 summer project.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:29.000
We can't bring Mississippi to America, but we can bring America to Mississippi.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:34.000
Because we found out we could not protect ourselves, we're going to be picked off one by one.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:41.000
We were organizing against the entire state apparatus of Mississippi and the country.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.000
The country was totally indifferent to voting.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:46.000
We had to nationalize this problem.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:50.000
We then challenged the Democratic Party in Atlantic City.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:55.000
And we supported in all of these endeavors by Martin Luther King.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:58.000
He supports us in the Congressional challenge.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:03.000
And then I asked him to do something harder than everything else he's ever done.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:08.000
I said, look Martin, we know that the voting rights act is going to pass.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:15.000
We need you to sign a memorandum along with myself, John Lewis, and other people saying

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:21.000
that we realize the voting rights act is going to pass, but the Congressional delegation from Mississippi still should be unseated.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:22.000
He does it.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:27.000
When he does that, they said, first of all, y'all got him, y'all forged his name.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.000
He sticks with us.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:34.000
And then what happens then, Julian, is, and this is David Garrow in his book.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:44.000
As you know, David Garrow is the chronicle of Martin Luther, makes the point that the Freedom Democratic Party in this memorandum had a larger impact on the voting rights act than did to him.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:47.000
David Garrow says it.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:53.000
Now, because what happened, and this all happened because of a guy named Michael Thelwell.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:58.000
Michael Thelwell gets a chance to attend the Leadership Conference meetings.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:04.000
And when you read the first proposal for the voting rights act, it's as weak as can be.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:09.000
The media would need 20 complaints, and the president may authorize it.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:14.000
We needed a greater trigger mechanism, and Section 5 was that trigger mechanism.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:20.000
But Section 5 wouldn't have been created unless we had the brought, we brought the Congressional challenge.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:27.000
We got 149 congressmen to say yes, the Congressional delegation from Mississippi should be seen.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:38.000
At the same time, the United States Supreme Court was here in a case called the United States versus Mississippi filed in 1962, argued in 1965 that it would have declared a vote.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:42.000
That it would have declared all of the laws in Mississippi on constitutional.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:47.000
Imagine if you will, if the Department of Justice had asked for emergency relief.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:50.000
I would have met new elections for everything in Mississippi.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:38:00.000
They didn't, because of course, Lyndon didn't want to fight with us in 1964, and then give us the gift of political impound in 1965.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:07.000
So what I'm saying, the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee leads to one of the most brilliant,

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:18.000
encumbering people involving empowerment process of attack on any oppressed state.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:22.000
And there was no state more oppressive than Mississippi.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:27.000
Lyndon Johnson said it best. There's America. There's the South and then there's Mississippi.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:44.000
You know, I've said, and I've had people object to me saying that you and I, and others like us, belong to the last generation of African Americans who have engaged in sustained mobilization in the 20th century.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:48.000
You and I are members of the last generation that have done that.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:54.000
Nothing has happened since we were of college age. You haven't seen any repetition of this. Why is that so?

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:59.000
Well, I tell you why we unique. I tell you why. We're not really unique.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:05.000
I appreciate the lottery win which you handle it. And I like to praise us.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:14.000
No, no, and I want to say very clearly we are entitled to praise, because we are a group of people who change the world, of course.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:22.000
And it is very important that we understand it. But when we look at operation understanding, we look at cultural leadership,

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:29.000
we look at the children's defense fund. I think the best training of what we did is now being done by those three groups.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:43.000
And the young people's project, headed by Moses' children. They are doing the kind of organizing we did. And what we must do is use the mantra of poor power right here.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:51.000
See, we got the literature. We got the mantra. We got the history. And what we have an opportunity to do and it is very necessary for us to do is

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:58.000
meld our experience. See, because what we have, what distinguishes us from a lot of other people.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:08.000
We saw total oppression and we brought about change. Every impediment to us, we turned it around. We turned it to an end.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:14.000
You can't register the vote. We're going to register the vote. You won't allow us to vote. We're going to vote anyway.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:24.000
You can't organize politically. We were not going to allow you to. We're going to put your name in the newspaper when we get to you.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:35.000
Thousands of people who have everything to risk. And they are willing to risk their lives and their children's lives and everything they have.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:42.000
And you can't do it secretly. That's success. That's called real political mobilization.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:54.000
Now, I think from January 23 to 26, the people who created this, the veterans of the Civil Rights Movement, Mississippi will be meeting.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:41:05.000
And on yesterday I read in the Washington Post about the Civil Rights Act, it's going online. The color purple and the NACP.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:17.000
See, my concern is how do we get those people to come down, see because as far as I'm concerned, the greatest organizers in America come out of Mississippi and SNCC.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:20.000
Who do you compare us to?

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:32.000
No, there's no comparison. And there's no mobilization of the sort we engaged in in the 1960s today. And I'm always asking, why is this so?

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.000
Let me answer your question, Fred.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:41.000
Let me answer your question, Fred. I mean, our community to mobilize in the way we did when we were young people and a little more vigorous than we are now.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:54.000
Let me give you the most logical and most practical answer. We're now given the perfect solution, the perfect opportunity that brings us back to that period.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:42:07.000
If we allow the Republicans to have control of the House and the Senate, except for the next two years, well, they don't control the Senate.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:17.000
Then we must forever write off that whole beautiful mantra that we created before them, because it's very clear.

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:27.000
I'm astounded that the political commentators look at a sense of equivalence between the Republican Party and the Democratic Party.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:36.000
There's none. The Republican Party is by definition obstructionist and wants to narrow the scope and function of government.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:45.000
The Democratic Party wants to do just the converse. So we now have a golden opportunity to fight for what we have, because it's all on the table.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:56.000
Everything you can imagine, given the Republicans need to destroy America as we know it, but we can prevent them.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:03.000
You see, a million of us who voted in 2008 didn't vote in the midterm elections.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:07.000
What we've got to do now is use all of our resources.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:17.000
For the next two years, I'm going to do nothing but push books, the mantra of SNCC, the example of SNCC as an organizing vehicle,

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:26.000
that I'm going to call on everyone who participated in the Freedom Elections in the Freedom Rides, in the Summer Project.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:30.000
You name them. It's time for action now.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:39.000
You see, and the reason I can do that with confidence is there's a difference between people who have made change, and there's a difference to people who have written about change.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:48.000
We are those who made change, and we now simply have to bring in young people to help us do it again.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:54.000
We see now a trouble attracting in sufficient numbers, young people today.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:44:06.000
I know you mentioned the Moses children who were doing wonderful work, and other groups who were doing wonderful work, but there's no equivalent today of the actions we engaged in in the 1960s.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:09.000
There's no equivalent anywhere in the country that I can see.

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:19.000
Let me say to you, my dear friend, if there was ever a time to get into motion to bring that about, it is now. We've got two years.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:23.000
Absolutely. If we don't act now, it's all lost.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:30.000
No, it will be lost, but it will be irretrievable. It's not a question of waiting ten years, and there'll be another flip.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:37.000
No, it won't happen. Well, let's not deal with these dim thoughts.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:47.000
I want you to give the people who will see this, some picture of how you occupied yourself, say in the summer of 1964, what would a typical week be for you?

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:54.000
If there is such a thing as a typical week in Mississippi in 1964, how would you occupy yourself? What would you do all day?

00:44:54.000 --> 00:45:01.000
I would stay in contact with people who organize. Where would you be located in the summer of 1964?

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:06.000
I would be in Hattiesburg, Mississippi, or in Jackson, or in Greenwood.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:12.000
Because the SNK headquarters was in Greenwood for the summer. That's right. And I was one of the first to go into Greenwood.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:21.000
And my job was to stay abreast of the political... Where did communities need help?

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:26.000
What kind of support did they need? How could we assist them in empowering people?

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:38.000
Because our position was SNK people were capable of... One or two SNK people going to a town, getting organized in two weeks, finding a place to stay.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:46.000
All on a salary of $10 a week when it was available. And we wanted to facilitate that as much as possible.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:54.000
We had to stay in touch with the political news, what was happening on the other side, how do we respond to it, what kind of press releases there?

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:59.000
And then we'd call you and Mary King and others when we needed help.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:08.000
But it meant setting up meetings, carrying out meetings, improving the skills of the leadership that was there.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:14.000
Harry Booy and I traveled to the state of Mississippi. Booy was a black Episcopalian.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.000
We're the most brilliant men I've ever met. He worked for the Delta Ministry.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:25.000
Well, the Delta Ministry was organized because I invited all religious groups to come to Hattiesburg in 1963.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:31.000
And then when SNK leaves Mississippi in 1966, they are replaced by the Delta Ministry.

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:36.000
Because the Delta... The new ally for the Freedom Democratic Party is the Delta Ministry.

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:44.000
And they support the Children's Defense Fund. The Children's Defense Fund, hidden by Edelman,

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:53.000
hires 3,000 people in Mississippi. So that instantly becomes a negative attraction to Senate to Stennis.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:57.000
And it must be killed so there's an attempt to destroy it.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:11.000
But it is the ability of SNK to continue to bring in forces to be used in its political methodology.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:19.000
We bring in the Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights under law. And I'm proud of the fact that they were to the left and people...

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:22.000
We got castigated for that. They're committed.

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:33.000
And I remember when Dave Dennis, Bob Moses, myself met with Kansler, Kanaui, and others.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:40.000
And we asked them, once I asked, I said, do you all agree that we will make the decisions and y'all do the litigating?

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:44.000
They said, yes. I was... And they never deviated from that.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:52.000
Now, I'm very proud that SNK took the position that we were not going to let anyone tell us what to do.

00:47:52.000 --> 00:48:01.000
I remember before, after Kennedy was killed, there was a request by Linda Johnson to be a moratorium on demonstrations.

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:09.000
And Theo Doe White had written a book, telling us that SNK were really communist and really dangerous people.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:15.000
And we analyzed that we had a meeting, a conference at Howard University.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:25.000
And what Biod Rustin spoke there, Baldwin spoke there, and the great socialist Norman Thomas spoke there.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:30.000
And Norman Thomas told us, look, we can't win by singing, we can't win unless we sing.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:38.000
And he said, you must understand, every program that we came up with, the Democrats litigated.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:43.000
I mean, turned into laws.

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:52.000
So, he was encouraged, the question was, would we be part of the nullification?

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:55.000
And we said, no, we're going to have it to some of the project.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:49:00.000
Now, some of the project was not universally accepted.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:05.000
Myself and Fannie Lou Hamer were two of the few people that supported the original.

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:17.000
And once Bob Moses comes back from McComb, when one of the witnesses was killed that evening that witnessed the Herb at Lee Killing, he then throws his weight behind.

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:18.000
Lewis, Lewis, Alan.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:19.000
Lewis, Alan.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:22.000
He then throws his weight behind the summer project, and it happens.

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:32.000
I think the summer project was one of the most creative, indigenous, empowering, nationalizing activities.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:35.000
And it couldn't have been pulled off by anyone but SNCC.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:42.000
Because SNCC was not answerable to anyone who could give it, tell it anything.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:50.000
When we pulled off the freedom of election, the voter education projects, we can no longer fund y'all.

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:53.000
And when you were doing this activity of SNCC, how much were you paid?

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:54.000
$10 a week.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.000
And this is before you were married?

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:57.000
That's right.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:00.000
Did you get married? Why you worked for SNCC?

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:01.000
Yes.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:02.000
Did your salary go up?

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:03.000
No.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:04.000
Mine did.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:05.000
But I had children.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.000
Good, glad you did, baby.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:08.000
I had children.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:17.000
Now, you mentioned earlier on, and I'm amazed that you recall, 714 Rose Street, which is the address of the Freedom House in Jackson.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.000
What would life be like the Freedom House?

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:20.000
Life would be like this.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:22.000
There would be people.

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:23.000
Bevel was there.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:25.000
Diane was there.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
Thomas Gaita was there.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:28.000
Paul Brooks was there.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:29.000
Dory Laddner was there.

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:30.000
Joyce Laddner was there.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:31.000
Moses was there.

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:32.000
I was there.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:33.000
LeVon Brown was there.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:41.000
And what it served as is a reconciliation post for everyone arrested in the Freedom Rides.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:44.000
Because when you got arrested in the Freedom Rides, you were tried in Jackson.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:48.000
And when you came to Jackson, you came to 714 Rose Street.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:54.000
And then we acquainted you with what was going on in the state and how you could be helpful when you went back to where you were.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:51:07.000
So it was this cross fertilization of activism that was uninhibited, that was indigenous, that was empowering, and that was answerable to no one.

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:18.000
But we were able to creatively involve all the major, the National Council of Churches gets committed once we, once they come to, to, uh, Hadisburg.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:21.000
They create the Delta Ministry, which lasts for 25 years.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:26.000
They also join us when we challenge the Congressional delegation.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:39.000
Uh, Breeden, uh, did Simmons, these are people from the National Council of Churches, they come to us and they talk to Michael Thowe while I said, what can we do about the Congressional challenge?

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:45.000
They said, what you can do is open doors where we don't have a civil rights movement.

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:50.000
We have churches and you can talk to the, uh, John, Jane, you know, you can talk to the Congressional, you know, you can talk to the Congressional, you can talk to the Congressional, you can talk to the Congressional, you can talk to the Congressional delegation.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:52:01.000
John, James Farmer, of course, and myself, got to talk to, Jert, Mr. Ford, who later becomes president forward, because his bishop called him and said, you got to talk to him.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:13.000
So what we've found is that the Labor Union's remember at the Howard University meeting, the FFLCO said to us, we're going to give you a contribution of $25,000.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:16.000
And we're going to set up a board of directors to tell you what to do.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:19.000
That lasted, you can imagine how long that lasted.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:30.000
But then if we look at, uh, when the summer project was agreed to, some people said to us, well, you know, William Sloan, Coffin has to head this.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:32.000
It never happened, Julian.

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:41.000
And then you, you remember the, the great meeting of, uh, a meeting that the, in New York about after the Democratic Convention.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:50.000
You got Gloucester Current, you got Roy Wilkins, you got Julian, I mean, uh, Courtland Cox, you got James Farmer, and this they look.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:55.000
Mississippi is now becoming a national and international paradigm.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:53:00.000
We can't allow the people that's running it down there to running the underbrush.

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:06.000
In your, in your people like Fannie Lou Hamer, like Fannie Lou Hamer, like in the underbrush, like, you got to step into it.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:07.000
Incredible.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:12.000
And Courtland said, was, don't you think you should talk to the people in Mississippi about this?

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:13.000
Listen, no.

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:20.000
See, what, what we, what we found was that we were creating something in Mississippi.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:35.000
And there, see, when you beat the best, and when you can organize around the worst, then you, you create a, a political example of what can be.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:45.000
Critic gains, who is one of the top demographics of the vote every year, wrote a letter in 1965.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:48.000
He said, I've toured the South.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:59.000
And if this SNCC, MFDP kind of operation is allowed to happen in the South, it will not be loyal to the national Democratic Party.

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:04.000
This letter is written in this entire, in local people by John Dippman.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:07.000
I got it and I gave it to Dippman. He put it in the book.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:11.000
He said, what we must do is quickly pass the Voting Rights Act.

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:14.000
So we can then bring blacks into the Democratic Party.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:26.000
So I just wanted to say that to say, look at how many other forces we were resonating with, and they put their own interpretation on it.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:34.000
The NEA and the AFT both send representatives to the summer project to capture the Freedom Curriculum.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:38.000
We meet in Connecticut, in Hartford, Connecticut years later.

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:46.000
And there's someone there who stands up and says, you know, we had a discussion about the, the, the curriculum for the Freedom Schools last week.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:59.000
So there's this tremendous infusion of bringing the political process to the average citizen.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:05.000
Now after, after 64, did you leave Mississippi? When did you move to D.C.?

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:08.000
I moved to D.C. in 1968.

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:18.000
I was a delegate to the Democratic Convention in 1968. We, we, we organized, Harry Bruin, I organized, what happened was this.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:23.000
The loyalists thought that they would be become part of the regular Democratic Party.

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:27.000
Bidwell Adams, my dear friend, was chairing the state convention.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:34.000
And he said, look, if you don't desegregate this delegation, you were wasting your bus fare to Chicago.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:42.000
And we waited for that to happen. And Aaron Henry and the loyalist, who were sent up as an alternative to destroy MFDP.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:46.000
They were unsuccessful. So then I said to them, let's join together.

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:54.000
The loyalists hooked up with the MFDP. We got 50% of the delegation. They got 50% and we were seated in 68.

00:55:54.000 --> 00:56:01.000
Now, in this eight days, Harry Bruin, myself, met with Charles Ebbers and Harding Carter.

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:06.000
And they looked at the names and said, how did y'all do it? I said, well, look, y'all had the money.

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:13.000
Y'all had the prestige. But we knew all of these people years before the new you.

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:21.000
So we went up and set up the nominee and we got Miss Raka. We got, we got our people.

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:24.000
Yeah.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:31.000
So when you came up here, you began to focus on DC issues. Tell us a little bit about that.

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:38.000
I had a good time up here. I began to fight for same-sex marriage.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:45.000
I began to fight for having the first presidential primary in Washington.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:51.000
So we could point out to the country the fact that we don't have congressional or senatorial representation.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:55.000
We get the first primary. But quite a few of the Democrats don't participate in it.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:57:02.000
Then I publicly lambraced them for that. I fight to do away with term limits.

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:10.000
I believe that we fought too many of us have died to allow the calendar to determine the political situation.

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:18.000
We do away with term limits here. I find this is a very creative city council.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:23.000
And it is one that I can operate conveniently with. I become an ANC commissioner.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:30.000
I begin in Delvin in economic development. I'm involved in everything that was developed in Columbia Heights.

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:37.000
Every one of those 37 proposals was brought to us. We were told to pick a developer to analyze and to grade them.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:46.000
We did that. So I'm built some of the political infrastructure of the city.

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:55.000
And I am very much of an activist. I supported Fenty for mayor.

00:57:55.000 --> 00:58:00.000
I supported the right hand because I have never- I remember in 1968.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:09.000
And you remember, I'm sure of yourself. We made a decision to move from the civil rights movement to carry the church with us into the political arena.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:16.000
And we forced wars to hate. We said we're not going to hate people. And we're going to choose the ballot instead.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:29.000
The Bible and the ballot in fusion. And then I see a campaign that to me was the real implementation of more hate than I've ever seen in my life.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:38.000
Fenty was not only defeated. He was turned into a hate caricature. And because of that, I joined him in the right hand.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:46.000
And of all the things I've done politically, I'm just as proud of that. Because one of the things I understand very clearly,

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:55.000
if black people ever make the mistake of separating our politics from our religion, we're damn not finished.

00:58:55.000 --> 00:59:03.000
At the same time, you mentioned same sex marriage. And same sex marriage is just anathema in many black homes.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:12.000
And in the black church community, one of the biggest opponents is Walter Fontroy, Reverend Walter Fontroy, who's Dr. King's lieutenant here.

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:21.000
So how do you manage in your practice of Christianity to balance this support for something that many black Christians just think is terrible?

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:30.000
Well, I think one of the best movements in that position was my wife.

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:38.000
Is my wife. My wife. And I met in when I went to California to raise money for SNCC. She comes to Mississippi.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:46.000
We leave there. We get married in Washington in 67. She supports me and everything I've done.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:54.000
She goes, she gets the job to help pay my way through Rutgers Law School. She's with me. She goes jail with me in Mississippi.

00:59:54.000 --> 01:00:04.000
We live together in Mississippi. My wife is white. And when I've gone to the hospital, she's come with me quite a few times. She saved my life.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:15.000
And I said to myself, can I really accept all of this and deny it to two other people of the same sex who are in love with one another?

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:27.000
And I couldn't. And I, you may, I may shock an amazement. I say this, but all of my power politics has been based on my religious beliefs.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:40.000
And I tell people, I said, look, when you said, when you told religiously to feed the hungry, clothes, the naked, visit those who are bound, it doesn't tell you to find out what the charges are.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:48.000
But whenever you attempt to do any of those three, you enter into the political arena. And that's all right, because there's no other way to do it.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:58.000
Because I teach political empowerment. And I first question I asked my class is, let's talk about something that's not political.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:07.000
Once we've gotten through that, then we go on to the question, what are you doing to enhance your political mobility and mortality and options?

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:16.000
Well, you know, I was thinking as you were talking there about the years we've known each other. And I frankly have not thought about you as a religious person.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:17.000
I understand.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:28.000
Probably I don't know that side of you at all, well, that's understandable. And I'm not offended by that at all, because I know I'm very happy with our relationship.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:37.000
I mean, I remember when you would share your poems with early and snake. And we both love books and we both have a very proud of what we've done.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:55.000
But I learned that we must be able to ethically transcend ourselves and put ourselves in other fellow shoes and then make a judgment.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:06.000
I have no problems with, or I justify before the City Council. And I said, look, I'm astounded by people wanting to vote on the nine other people human rights.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:10.000
I said, we didn't, we didn't sacrifice lives for that.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:21.000
We should, the vote should be used to bill, to strengthen. It should be used affirmatively. And quite a few people agree to me on that.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:29.000
So I think the beauty of politics, even though it has a bad name right now, will be revived.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:40.000
Because in order to save this country, we're going to have to revive it. And I think I look at it as a good, good, good journey.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:50.000
Because as long as you have a country in which six out of ten people don't know the difference between the various layers of government,

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:59.000
how can you really create public opinion about affirmative and moving? Jefferson said it very clearly.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:05.000
In order to have a Republican-style government, you have to have an informed electorate.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:11.000
My dear friend, we have a most tragically misinformed directorate right now.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:16.000
Okay.

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:24.000
